1
00:04:19,760 --> 00:04:22,846
Who's that stumbling around
in the dark?

2
00:04:23,013 --> 00:04:26,850
State your business
or prepare to get winged.

3
00:04:27,017 --> 00:04:31,772
Calm yourselves, gentlemen.
I mean you no harm.

4
00:04:32,397 --> 00:04:34,983
I'm simply a fellow weary traveler.

5
00:04:35,150 --> 00:04:37,194
Whoa, boy.

6
00:04:38,528 --> 00:04:40,238
Good cold evening, gentlemen.

7
00:04:40,405 --> 00:04:44,743
I'm looking for a pair of slave traders that
go by the name of the Speck Brothers.

8
00:04:44,910 --> 00:04:46,328
Might that be you?

9
00:04:47,829 --> 00:04:50,665
-Who wants to know?
-Well, I do.

10
00:04:50,832 --> 00:04:53,543
I'm Dr. King Schultz.
This is my horse, Fritz.

11
00:04:54,419 --> 00:04:57,506
-What kind of doctor?
-Dentist.

12
00:04:57,714 --> 00:04:59,382
Now, are you the Speck Brothers?

13
00:04:59,549 --> 00:05:02,385
Did you purchase those men
at the Greenville auction?

14
00:05:02,552 --> 00:05:05,138
-So what?
-So I wish to parley with you.

15
00:05:05,305 --> 00:05:06,348
Speak English.

16
00:05:07,057 --> 00:05:08,642
I'm sorry.

17
00:05:08,809 --> 00:05:11,019
Please forgive me.
It is a second language.

18
00:05:11,186 --> 00:05:14,564
Now, amongst your inventory,
I've been led to believe...

19
00:05:14,731 --> 00:05:17,025
...is a specimen I'm keen to acquire.

20
00:05:17,192 --> 00:05:18,652
Hello, you poor devils.

21
00:05:19,986 --> 00:05:22,823
Is there one amongst you
who was formerly a resident...

22
00:05:22,989 --> 00:05:25,992
...of the Carrucan plantation?

23
00:05:26,910 --> 00:05:29,037
I'm from the Carrucan plantation.

24
00:05:30,872 --> 00:05:32,249
Who said that?

25
00:06:19,170 --> 00:06:20,964
What's your name?

26
00:06:24,968 --> 00:06:26,720
Django.

27
00:06:27,012 --> 00:06:29,556
Then you are exactly the one
I'm looking for.

28
00:06:31,349 --> 00:06:33,727
Do you know who
the Brittle Brothers are?

29
00:06:37,230 --> 00:06:38,273
Who are they?

30
00:06:40,775 --> 00:06:42,444
Big John.

31
00:06:43,111 --> 00:06:44,571
Ellis.

32
00:06:45,780 --> 00:06:47,073
Roger.

33
00:06:47,240 --> 00:06:50,035
Sometime they call him Little Raj.

34
00:06:51,036 --> 00:06:53,412
They was overseers
at the Carrucan plantation.

35
00:06:53,580 --> 00:06:54,664
Not anymore.

36
00:06:57,751 --> 00:07:02,047
Tell me, if you were to see any
of these three gentlemen again...

37
00:07:02,213 --> 00:07:04,507
-...would you recognize them?
-Hey.

38
00:07:05,216 --> 00:07:07,719
-Stop talking to him like that.
-Like what?

39
00:07:08,136 --> 00:07:09,179
Like that.

40
00:07:09,346 --> 00:07:11,848
My good man,
I'm simply trying to ascertain--

41
00:07:12,015 --> 00:07:13,892
Speak English, goddamn it.

42
00:07:14,059 --> 00:07:16,061
Everybody calm down.

43
00:07:16,227 --> 00:07:19,898
I'm simply a customer trying to
conduct a transaction.

44
00:07:20,065 --> 00:07:23,026
I don't care. No sale. Now, off with you.

45
00:07:23,610 --> 00:07:26,112
Don't be ridiculous.
Of course they're for sale.

46
00:07:27,030 --> 00:07:28,448
Move it.

47
00:07:28,698 --> 00:07:33,411
My good man, did you simply get
carried away with your dramatic gesture...

48
00:07:33,578 --> 00:07:37,415
...or are you pointing your weapon
at me with lethal intention?

49
00:07:38,708 --> 00:07:40,418
Last chance, fancy pants.

50
00:07:41,670 --> 00:07:44,089
Oh, very well.

51
00:08:12,951 --> 00:08:17,288
I'm sorry to put a bullet in your beast.
I didn't want you to do anything rash...

52
00:08:17,455 --> 00:08:20,041
...before you had a moment
to come to your senses.

53
00:08:20,208 --> 00:08:23,586
You goddamn son of a bitch.

54
00:08:23,837 --> 00:08:25,213
You shot Roscoe!

55
00:08:25,380 --> 00:08:26,464
Well....

56
00:08:26,673 --> 00:08:28,091
And you killed Ace!

57
00:08:28,258 --> 00:08:31,302
I only shot your brother
once he threatened to shoot me.

58
00:08:31,469 --> 00:08:32,929
And I do believe I have--

59
00:08:33,096 --> 00:08:34,347
One, two, three, four.

60
00:08:34,514 --> 00:08:37,434
--five witnesses
who can attest to that fact.

61
00:08:37,600 --> 00:08:40,103
-Damn leg's busted.
-No doubt.

62
00:08:40,270 --> 00:08:43,440
Now, if you could keep your caterwauling
down to a minimum...

63
00:08:43,606 --> 00:08:47,110
...I'd like to finish my line of inquiry
with young Django.

64
00:08:50,530 --> 00:08:52,407
God-fucking-damn it!

65
00:08:52,574 --> 00:08:54,075
As I was saying...

66
00:08:54,242 --> 00:08:58,455
...if you were to see the Brittle Brothers
again, you could recognize them?

67
00:08:58,621 --> 00:08:59,998
Yeah.

68
00:09:00,540 --> 00:09:01,708
Sold American!

69
00:09:01,875 --> 00:09:03,001
So, Mr. Speck?

70
00:09:03,168 --> 00:09:05,879
Mr. Speck?
How much for young Django here?

71
00:09:11,176 --> 00:09:13,928
That iron is nasty business.

72
00:09:19,059 --> 00:09:21,603
Oh, could you hold this for a moment?

73
00:09:23,229 --> 00:09:24,272
Thank you.

74
00:09:24,439 --> 00:09:26,983
Django? Get up on that horse.

75
00:09:27,150 --> 00:09:28,735
Also, if I were you...

76
00:09:28,902 --> 00:09:33,281
...I'd take that winter coat
the dear departed Speck left behind.

77
00:09:46,961 --> 00:09:51,174
Nigger!
Don't you touch my brother's coat.

78
00:10:02,352 --> 00:10:04,687
Goddamn it!

79
00:10:08,691 --> 00:10:11,402
One hundred, 10...

80
00:10:11,861 --> 00:10:13,404
...20...

81
00:10:13,780 --> 00:10:15,406
...and 5...

82
00:10:16,491 --> 00:10:17,951
...for young Django here.

83
00:10:18,118 --> 00:10:20,328
And since he won't be
needing it anymore...

84
00:10:20,495 --> 00:10:22,831
...I'd like to purchase
your brother's nag.

85
00:10:23,581 --> 00:10:25,708
Also, Mr. Speck...

86
00:10:25,875 --> 00:10:29,796
...I'm afraid I will require a bill of sale.
Do you have one?

87
00:10:30,380 --> 00:10:33,466
You go to hell, dentist.

88
00:10:33,800 --> 00:10:35,593
I thought not.

89
00:10:35,760 --> 00:10:39,472
No worries. I come prepared.

90
00:10:43,518 --> 00:10:45,103
Thank you.

91
00:10:45,270 --> 00:10:49,065
This will serve nicely as a bill of sale.

92
00:11:06,457 --> 00:11:09,919
Now, as to you poor devils....

93
00:11:10,211 --> 00:11:12,046
So, as I see it...

94
00:11:12,213 --> 00:11:15,133
...when it comes to the subject
of what to do next...

95
00:11:15,300 --> 00:11:18,136
...you gentlemen have two choices.

96
00:11:18,303 --> 00:11:19,429
One:

97
00:11:19,596 --> 00:11:23,391
Once I'm gone, you could lift
that beast off the remaining Speck...

98
00:11:23,558 --> 00:11:25,560
...then carry him to the nearest town.

99
00:11:25,727 --> 00:11:29,314
Which would be at least 37 miles
back the way you came.

100
00:11:29,480 --> 00:11:30,732
Or two:

101
00:11:31,524 --> 00:11:33,651
You could unshackle yourselves...

102
00:11:33,818 --> 00:11:35,111
...take that rifle...

103
00:11:35,278 --> 00:11:38,281
...put a bullet in his head,
bury the two of them deep...

104
00:11:38,448 --> 00:11:42,160
...and then make your way to a more
enlightened area of this country.

105
00:11:42,535 --> 00:11:43,745
Choice is yours.

106
00:11:43,912 --> 00:11:48,249
Oh, and on the off chance there are any
astronomy aficionados amongst you...

107
00:11:48,416 --> 00:11:51,502
...the North Star is that one.

108
00:11:52,879 --> 00:11:54,464
Ta-ta.

109
00:12:10,897 --> 00:12:14,609
Now, wait a minute, fellas.
Let's talk about this.

110
00:12:18,446 --> 00:12:22,367
You gotta be reasonable
in a situation like this.

111
00:12:23,368 --> 00:12:26,496
I'm not a bad guy.
I'm just doing my job.

112
00:12:26,663 --> 00:12:30,208
Blueberry, didn't I
give you my last apple?

113
00:12:30,375 --> 00:12:31,626
Tell you what, boys:

114
00:12:31,793 --> 00:12:35,546
Take me to the doc in El Paso,
I'll get you your freedom.

115
00:12:35,713 --> 00:12:36,881
No. No, please.

116
00:13:24,762 --> 00:13:26,139
All right, now.

117
00:13:26,347 --> 00:13:28,807
I'd like you to take two of these
tonight...

118
00:13:28,975 --> 00:13:30,935
...and then in the morning....

119
00:13:32,895 --> 00:13:34,647
That's a nigger on a horse.

120
00:14:00,173 --> 00:14:02,008
What's everybody staring at?

121
00:14:02,175 --> 00:14:05,136
They ain't never seen no nigger
on a horse before.

122
00:14:28,034 --> 00:14:30,244
Good morning, innkeeper.

123
00:14:31,496 --> 00:14:33,915
Two beers for two weary travelers.

124
00:14:34,082 --> 00:14:38,378
It's still a bit early.
We won't be open for another hour.

125
00:14:38,544 --> 00:14:40,463
By then, we'll be serving breakfast.

126
00:14:43,758 --> 00:14:45,927
What the hell
you think you're doing, boy?

127
00:14:46,094 --> 00:14:48,388
Get that nigger out of here.

128
00:14:53,142 --> 00:14:54,685
Help! Help!

129
00:14:54,852 --> 00:14:55,895
Innkeeper!

130
00:14:56,354 --> 00:14:59,273
Remember, get the sheriff,
not the marshal.

131
00:14:59,440 --> 00:15:01,526
Sheriff! Help!

132
00:15:01,692 --> 00:15:03,403
Alas...

133
00:15:04,362 --> 00:15:07,448
...now we must act
as our own bartender.

134
00:15:09,409 --> 00:15:11,285
Sit down, my boy.

135
00:15:20,962 --> 00:15:22,880
What kind of dentist are you?

136
00:15:24,882 --> 00:15:29,512
Despite that cart,
I haven't practiced dentistry in five years.

137
00:15:33,724 --> 00:15:36,769
But these days,
I practice a new profession:

138
00:15:39,313 --> 00:15:40,565
Bounty hunter.

139
00:15:47,238 --> 00:15:49,490
Do you know what a bounty hunter is?

140
00:15:49,657 --> 00:15:50,825
No.

141
00:15:50,992 --> 00:15:52,160
Well...

142
00:15:53,619 --> 00:15:57,748
...the way the slave trade
deals in human lives for cash...

143
00:15:57,915 --> 00:16:00,585
...a bounty hunter deals in corpses.

144
00:16:01,669 --> 00:16:03,004
Hat.

145
00:16:16,309 --> 00:16:18,895
The state places a bounty
on a man's head.

146
00:16:19,061 --> 00:16:21,731
I track that man, I find that man,
I kill that man.

147
00:16:21,898 --> 00:16:25,943
After I've killed him, I transport
that man's corpse back to the authorities.

148
00:16:26,110 --> 00:16:28,821
Sometimes that's easier said
than done.

149
00:16:28,988 --> 00:16:33,618
I show that corpse to the authorities,
proving indeed, I truly have killed him.

150
00:16:33,784 --> 00:16:36,537
At which point the authorities
pay me the bounty.

151
00:16:36,704 --> 00:16:40,208
So, like slavery,
it's a flesh-for-cash business.

152
00:16:41,792 --> 00:16:42,835
What's a bounty?

153
00:16:46,714 --> 00:16:48,216
It's like a reward.

154
00:16:48,716 --> 00:16:51,761
You kill people?
And they give you a reward?

155
00:16:52,470 --> 00:16:53,804
Certain people, yeah.

156
00:16:54,138 --> 00:16:55,765
Bad people?

157
00:16:56,349 --> 00:16:58,935
Badder they are, bigger the reward.

158
00:16:59,393 --> 00:17:01,437
Which brings me to you.

159
00:17:01,771 --> 00:17:05,608
And I must admit, I'm at a bit of
a quandary when it comes to you.

160
00:17:06,317 --> 00:17:08,611
On one hand, I despise slavery.

161
00:17:08,778 --> 00:17:11,989
On the other hand, I need your help.

162
00:17:12,156 --> 00:17:15,451
If you're not in a position to refuse,
all the better.

163
00:17:16,244 --> 00:17:21,040
So for the time being, I'm gonna make
this slavery malarkey work to my benefit.

164
00:17:21,541 --> 00:17:24,252
Still, having said that...

165
00:17:25,002 --> 00:17:26,170
...I feel guilty.

166
00:17:27,880 --> 00:17:33,177
So I would like the two of us
to enter into an agreement.

167
00:17:40,059 --> 00:17:42,019
I'm looking for the Brittle Brothers.

168
00:17:46,816 --> 00:17:50,111
However, at this endeavor,
I'm at a slight disadvantage...

169
00:17:50,611 --> 00:17:53,489
...insofar as I don't know
what they look like.

170
00:17:54,782 --> 00:17:57,535
But you do. Don't you?

171
00:17:57,702 --> 00:17:59,912
I know what they look like, all right.

172
00:18:00,079 --> 00:18:01,205
Good.

173
00:18:01,414 --> 00:18:03,541
So here's my agreement.

174
00:18:03,708 --> 00:18:05,793
You travel with me until we find them.

175
00:18:05,960 --> 00:18:07,169
Where we going?

176
00:18:07,336 --> 00:18:11,924
I hear at least two of them are overseeing
in Gatlinburg, but I don't know where.

177
00:18:12,300 --> 00:18:16,846
That means we visit every plantation
in Gatlinburg till we find them.

178
00:18:17,013 --> 00:18:18,639
And when we find them...

179
00:18:19,140 --> 00:18:21,225
...you point them out and I kill them.

180
00:18:23,227 --> 00:18:24,687
You do that...

181
00:18:24,937 --> 00:18:29,233
...I agree to give you your freedom,
$25 per Brittle Brother.

182
00:18:29,400 --> 00:18:30,776
That's $75.

183
00:18:30,943 --> 00:18:35,323
And, as if on cue,
here comes the sheriff.

184
00:18:42,371 --> 00:18:45,833
Okay, boys. Fun's over.

185
00:18:46,876 --> 00:18:48,419
Come on out.

186
00:18:51,380 --> 00:18:55,509
All right, folks, calm down.

187
00:18:56,093 --> 00:18:58,262
Go about your business.

188
00:18:58,638 --> 00:19:01,182
These jokers will be gone soon.

189
00:19:03,142 --> 00:19:08,314
Now, why y'all wanna come into my town
and start trouble?

190
00:19:08,481 --> 00:19:11,859
And scare all these nice people.

191
00:19:13,110 --> 00:19:15,863
You ain't got nothing better to do...

192
00:19:16,030 --> 00:19:19,158
...than to come into Bill Sharp's town...

193
00:19:19,325 --> 00:19:22,411
...and show your ass?

194
00:19:29,960 --> 00:19:32,463
What'd you just do to our sheriff?

195
00:19:45,267 --> 00:19:47,478
Now you can get the marshal.

196
00:19:48,938 --> 00:19:51,148
Marshal! Marshal!

197
00:19:51,315 --> 00:19:53,651
-Should we wait inside?
-Can we just leave?

198
00:19:53,818 --> 00:19:55,152
After you.

199
00:19:57,613 --> 00:20:01,367
Move that buckboard a long ways
across the street from the saloon.

200
00:20:01,742 --> 00:20:04,704
I want six men, six rifles behind it.

201
00:20:04,870 --> 00:20:07,123
I want two men,
two rifles up on this roof.

202
00:20:07,289 --> 00:20:09,417
Two men, two rifles on that roof.

203
00:20:09,625 --> 00:20:12,461
All the barrels aimed at that front door.

204
00:20:12,962 --> 00:20:15,923
Somebody get poor Bill
out of the goddamn street.

205
00:20:16,924 --> 00:20:18,843
You in the saloon.

206
00:20:19,510 --> 00:20:22,972
We got 100 rifles aimed at
every way out of that building.

207
00:20:23,389 --> 00:20:26,726
You got one chance
to get out of this alive.

208
00:20:27,435 --> 00:20:32,106
You and your nigger come out right now,
and I mean right now.

209
00:20:33,149 --> 00:20:36,736
Is this the marshal I have the pleasure
of addressing?

210
00:20:37,194 --> 00:20:38,654
Yes, it is.

211
00:20:38,821 --> 00:20:40,948
This is U.S. Marshal Gill Tatum.

212
00:20:41,115 --> 00:20:43,284
<i>Na wunderbar, </i>marshal.

213
00:20:43,826 --> 00:20:47,496
I have relieved myself of all weapons...

214
00:20:47,830 --> 00:20:50,624
...and just as you have instructed...

215
00:20:50,791 --> 00:20:53,461
...I am ready to step outside...

216
00:20:53,627 --> 00:20:57,548
...with my hands raised
above my head.

217
00:20:58,841 --> 00:21:01,093
I trust, as a representative...

218
00:21:01,260 --> 00:21:04,805
...of the criminal justice system
of the United States of America...

219
00:21:04,972 --> 00:21:07,975
...I shan't be shot down in the street...

220
00:21:08,142 --> 00:21:10,811
...by either you or your deputies...

221
00:21:10,978 --> 00:21:13,731
...before I've had my day in court.

222
00:21:13,981 --> 00:21:15,983
You mean like you did our sheriff?

223
00:21:16,150 --> 00:21:18,194
Shot him down like a dog in the street.

224
00:21:18,360 --> 00:21:20,613
Yes, that's exactly what I mean.

225
00:21:20,780 --> 00:21:22,865
Do I have your word as a lawman...

226
00:21:23,032 --> 00:21:26,827
...not to shoot me down
like a dog in the street?

227
00:21:29,789 --> 00:21:33,334
Well, much as we'd all enjoy
seeing something like that...

228
00:21:33,501 --> 00:21:36,462
...ain't nobody gonna cheat
the hangman in my town.

229
00:21:37,296 --> 00:21:40,299
Fair enough, marshal. Here we come.

230
00:21:42,176 --> 00:21:44,220
They're a little tense out there...

231
00:21:44,386 --> 00:21:48,098
...so don't make any quick movements
and let me do the talking.

232
00:21:49,475 --> 00:21:50,935
Come ahead.

233
00:21:58,025 --> 00:22:00,986
-You unarmed?
-Yes, indeed we are.

234
00:22:01,654 --> 00:22:04,949
Marshal Tatum,
may I address you and your deputies...

235
00:22:05,115 --> 00:22:07,660
...and apparently the entire town
of Daughtrey...

236
00:22:07,827 --> 00:22:10,454
...as to the incident that just occurred?

237
00:22:11,163 --> 00:22:12,414
Go on.

238
00:22:12,623 --> 00:22:13,791
Thank you.

239
00:22:13,958 --> 00:22:15,960
My name is Dr. King Schultz.

240
00:22:16,126 --> 00:22:19,505
Like yourself, marshal,
I'm a servant of the court.

241
00:22:19,672 --> 00:22:21,465
The man lying dead in the dirt...

242
00:22:21,632 --> 00:22:25,427
...who the good people of Daughtrey
saw fit to elect as their sheriff...

243
00:22:25,594 --> 00:22:27,721
...who went by the name of Bill Sharp...

244
00:22:27,888 --> 00:22:31,934
...is actually a wanted outlaw
by the name of Willard Peck...

245
00:22:32,101 --> 00:22:34,687
...with a price on his head of $200.

246
00:22:34,854 --> 00:22:37,857
Now that's $200, dead or alive.

247
00:22:38,023 --> 00:22:39,316
The hell, you say.

248
00:22:39,483 --> 00:22:43,404
I'm aware this is probably
disconcerting news.

249
00:22:43,571 --> 00:22:45,030
But I'm willing to wager...

250
00:22:45,197 --> 00:22:49,451
...this man was elected sheriff
sometime in the past two years?

251
00:22:50,536 --> 00:22:53,622
-Yeah.
-I know this because three years ago...

252
00:22:53,789 --> 00:22:57,251
...he was rustling cattle from the
B.C. Corrigan Cattle Company...

253
00:22:57,418 --> 00:22:58,669
...of Lubbock, Texas.

254
