00:43:16,719 --> 00:43:19,013
Well, fuck all y'all. I'm going home.

504
00:43:19,180 --> 00:43:21,265
Now, I watched my wife work all day...

505
00:43:21,432 --> 00:43:25,311
...getting 30 bags together
for you ungrateful sons of bitches...

506
00:43:25,478 --> 00:43:29,232
...and all I can hear is
criticize, criticize, criticize.

507
00:43:29,398 --> 00:43:32,944
From now on,
don't ask me or mine for nothing.

508
00:43:33,611 --> 00:43:36,823
Now, look.
Let's not forget why we're here.

509
00:43:36,989 --> 00:43:41,577
We got a killer nigger over that hill there,
and we gotta make a lesson out of him.

510
00:43:41,744 --> 00:43:45,540
Okay, I'm confused.
Are the bags on or off?

511
00:43:45,748 --> 00:43:50,461
I think we all think
the bag was a nice idea.

512
00:43:50,628 --> 00:43:51,671
Yeah.

513
00:43:51,838 --> 00:43:55,675
But, not pointing any fingers,
they could have been done better.

514
00:43:56,926 --> 00:44:00,555
So how about no bags this time...

515
00:44:00,721 --> 00:44:05,476
...but next time we do the bags right
and then we go full regalia.

516
00:44:05,643 --> 00:44:07,687
-I like that idea.
-You get my vote.

517
00:44:07,854 --> 00:44:08,896
Wait a minute.

518
00:44:09,480 --> 00:44:11,315
I didn't say no bags.

519
00:44:11,482 --> 00:44:13,484
But nobody can see.

520
00:44:13,901 --> 00:44:16,779
-So?
-So it'd be nice to see.

521
00:44:17,196 --> 00:44:21,701
Goddamn it! This is a raid!
I can't see, you can't see.

522
00:44:22,118 --> 00:44:27,206
So what? All that matters is can
the fucking horse see. That's a raid!

523
00:44:28,708 --> 00:44:30,042
Sons of bitches!

524
00:44:30,710 --> 00:44:32,670
I can't see shit!

525
00:44:32,879 --> 00:44:36,883
There he is. Get that nigger
out from under that wagon.

526
00:44:37,049 --> 00:44:39,260
And get that nigger lover
out of the wagon.

527
00:44:39,427 --> 00:44:41,888
-That nigger ain't down here, Big Daddy.
-What?

528
00:44:42,054 --> 00:44:43,931
-They tricked us.
-Where are they?

529
00:44:53,065 --> 00:44:54,233
Bull's-eye.

530
00:44:57,028 --> 00:44:58,070
Look at them run.

531
00:45:03,242 --> 00:45:05,745
Yeah, cowards tend to do that.

532
00:45:13,878 --> 00:45:15,588
Goddamn it!

533
00:45:19,759 --> 00:45:21,510
Would you care to?

534
00:45:28,392 --> 00:45:30,561
Can't see shit out of this.

535
00:45:30,853 --> 00:45:32,897
-He's getting away.
-I got him.

536
00:45:34,982 --> 00:45:36,525
Big Daddy's getting away.

537
00:45:36,692 --> 00:45:37,860
I got him.

538
00:45:53,084 --> 00:45:54,126
Got him.

539
00:46:00,132 --> 00:46:02,385
The kid's a natural.

540
00:46:12,853 --> 00:46:15,815
How you know Broomhilda's
first masters was German?

541
00:46:16,773 --> 00:46:18,609
Broomhilda's a German name.

542
00:46:18,775 --> 00:46:21,862
If they named her,
it stands to reason they'd be German.

543
00:46:22,029 --> 00:46:24,907
Lots of gals where you're from
named Broomhilda?

544
00:46:25,074 --> 00:46:27,994
Broomhilda is the name
of a character...

545
00:46:28,160 --> 00:46:32,081
...in the most popular
of all the German legends.

546
00:46:32,248 --> 00:46:34,125
There's a story about Broomhilda?

547
00:46:34,292 --> 00:46:36,127
Oh, yes, there is.

548
00:46:42,091 --> 00:46:43,217
Do you know it?

549
00:46:43,384 --> 00:46:45,553
Oh, every German knows that story.

550
00:46:51,934 --> 00:46:54,228
Would you like me to tell you?

551
00:46:55,021 --> 00:47:01,610
Well, Broomhilda was a princess.

552
00:47:02,778 --> 00:47:06,741
She was a daughter of Wotan,
god of all gods.

553
00:47:07,824 --> 00:47:11,078
Anyway, her father is really mad at her.

554
00:47:11,245 --> 00:47:12,455
What she do?

555
00:47:13,414 --> 00:47:14,957
I can't exactly remember.

556
00:47:15,124 --> 00:47:17,793
She disobeys him in some way.

557
00:47:17,960 --> 00:47:21,130
So he puts her on top of the mountain.

558
00:47:21,505 --> 00:47:22,923
Broomhilda's on a mountain?

559
00:47:23,090 --> 00:47:27,094
It's a German legend, there's going to be
a mountain in there somewhere.

560
00:47:27,261 --> 00:47:31,599
And he puts a fire-breathing dragon
there to guard the mountain.

561
00:47:33,059 --> 00:47:38,689
And he surrounds her
in a circle of hellfire.

562
00:47:39,732 --> 00:47:44,445
And there, Broomhilda shall remain...

563
00:47:45,279 --> 00:47:50,534
...unless a hero arises
brave enough to save her.

564
00:47:51,577 --> 00:47:53,371
Does a fella arise?

565
00:47:53,537 --> 00:47:56,540
Yes, Django, as a matter of fact,
he does.

566
00:47:56,707 --> 00:47:58,542
A fella named Siegfried.

567
00:47:59,210 --> 00:48:01,379
Does Siegfried save her?

568
00:48:02,797 --> 00:48:05,299
Quite spectacularly so.

569
00:48:06,175 --> 00:48:10,221
He scales the mountain,
because he's not afraid of it.

570
00:48:10,971 --> 00:48:15,059
He slays the dragon,
because he's not afraid of him.

571
00:48:15,393 --> 00:48:18,312
And he walks through hellfire...

572
00:48:20,147 --> 00:48:23,025
...because Broomhilda's worth it.

573
00:48:26,612 --> 00:48:28,531
I know how he feel.

574
00:48:29,740 --> 00:48:32,909
I think I'm just starting to realize that.

575
00:48:38,124 --> 00:48:42,628
Now, look, Django...

576
00:48:45,339 --> 00:48:49,677
...I don't doubt that one day
you'll save your lady love...

577
00:48:50,386 --> 00:48:54,223
...but I can't let you go to Greenville
in a good conscience.

578
00:48:55,224 --> 00:48:59,603
A slave auction town in Mississippi
isn't the place for you to visit.

579
00:48:59,770 --> 00:49:02,731
Free or not, it's just too dangerous.

580
00:49:05,651 --> 00:49:07,987
But let me ask you a question.

581
00:49:15,119 --> 00:49:17,913
How do you like
the bounty hunting business?

582
00:49:19,206 --> 00:49:21,667
Kill white folks and they pay you for it?

583
00:49:22,334 --> 00:49:23,627
What's not to like?

584
00:49:23,794 --> 00:49:25,962
Now, I have to admit,
we make a good team.

585
00:49:26,130 --> 00:49:29,467
I thought you was mad at me
for killing Big John and Little Raj.

586
00:49:29,633 --> 00:49:33,846
Yeah, you were a tad overzealous,
but normally that's a good thing.

587
00:49:34,430 --> 00:49:36,724
How'd you like to partner up
for the winter?

588
00:49:36,891 --> 00:49:38,559
What you mean, "partner up"?

589
00:49:39,018 --> 00:49:43,063
You work with me
through the winter till the snow melts...

590
00:49:44,190 --> 00:49:46,192
...I give you a third of my bounties.

591
00:49:47,443 --> 00:49:51,447
So we make some money this winter,
and when the snow melts...

592
00:49:51,864 --> 00:49:54,658
...I'll take you to Greenville myself...

593
00:49:54,825 --> 00:49:58,162
...and we'll find
where they sent your wife.

594
00:50:02,041 --> 00:50:04,418
Why you care what happen to me?

595
00:50:05,586 --> 00:50:07,671
Why you care if I find my wife?

596
00:50:07,838 --> 00:50:09,131
Frankly...

597
00:50:10,549 --> 00:50:13,260
...I've never given anybody
their freedom before.

598
00:50:13,427 --> 00:50:17,681
And now that I have,
I feel vaguely responsible for you.

599
00:50:18,474 --> 00:50:22,645
Plus, when a German meets a real-life
Siegfried, that's kind of a big deal.

600
00:50:24,647 --> 00:50:26,899
As a German, I'm obliged to help you...

601
00:50:27,066 --> 00:50:30,736
...on your quest to rescue
your beloved Broomhilda.

602
00:52:39,698 --> 00:52:40,741
You got her.

603
00:52:48,874 --> 00:52:52,586
What happened to Mr. "I Wanna
Shoot White Folks For Money"?

604
00:52:52,795 --> 00:52:54,129
His son's with him.

605
00:52:54,296 --> 00:52:57,216
Well, good.
He'll have a loved one with him.

606
00:52:57,383 --> 00:53:00,219
Maybe even share a last word.

607
00:53:01,637 --> 00:53:03,764
That's better than most of them get.

608
00:53:03,931 --> 00:53:06,558
Damn sight better than he deserves.

609
00:53:14,525 --> 00:53:16,068
Put down the rifle.

610
00:53:18,779 --> 00:53:20,948
Don't worry, I'm not mad at you.

611
00:53:21,365 --> 00:53:24,118
Let's take out Smitty Bacall's handbill.

612
00:53:27,496 --> 00:53:29,456
Now, read it aloud.

613
00:53:29,915 --> 00:53:32,208
Consider that today's lesson.

614
00:53:34,169 --> 00:53:37,089
"Wanted. Dead or alive.

615
00:53:37,881 --> 00:53:41,217
Smitty Bacall
and the Smitty Bacall G--"

616
00:53:42,010 --> 00:53:43,887
-Gang.
-"Gang."

617
00:53:44,346 --> 00:53:47,975
"For murder and stagecoach...

618
00:53:49,601 --> 00:53:50,894
...robbery.

619
00:53:51,061 --> 00:53:52,604
Seven-zero-zero-zero--"

620
00:53:52,771 --> 00:53:54,064
Seven thousand.

621
00:53:54,230 --> 00:53:55,649
Thousand.

622
00:53:55,816 --> 00:53:59,778
"Seven thousand dollars
for Smitty Bacall...

623
00:53:59,945 --> 00:54:05,241
...$1500 for each of his...

624
00:54:05,409 --> 00:54:06,994
...gang m--"

625
00:54:07,536 --> 00:54:08,620
Mem...?

626
00:54:08,787 --> 00:54:10,289
"Members.

627
00:54:10,706 --> 00:54:15,251
Known members of the Smitty Bacall
Gang are as follas:"

628
00:54:15,419 --> 00:54:17,337
-Follows.
-"Follows."

629
00:54:17,629 --> 00:54:20,924
"Dandy Michaels, Gerald Nash and--"

630
00:54:22,426 --> 00:54:24,344
Crazy Craig Koons.

631
00:54:25,179 --> 00:54:27,556
That is who Smitty Bacall is.

632
00:54:28,015 --> 00:54:33,020
If Smitty Bacall wanted to start a farm
at 22, they would never have printed that.

633
00:54:33,479 --> 00:54:36,815
But Smitty Bacall
wanted to rob stagecoaches...

634
00:54:36,982 --> 00:54:39,359
...and he didn't mind
killing people to do it.

635
00:54:40,235 --> 00:54:43,322
Do you want to save your wife
by doing what I do?

636
00:54:44,656 --> 00:54:46,200
This is what I do.

637
00:54:46,366 --> 00:54:50,078
I kill people and sell their corpses
for cash.

638
00:54:50,829 --> 00:54:54,374
This corpse is worth $7000.

639
00:54:54,541 --> 00:54:57,336
Now quit your pussyfooting
and shoot him.

640
00:55:07,137 --> 00:55:08,347
Pa?

641
00:55:08,555 --> 00:55:10,057
Pa!

642
00:55:18,482 --> 00:55:22,152
Here. You need to keep
this Smitty Bacall handbill.

643
00:55:22,318 --> 00:55:23,362
Why?

644
00:55:23,529 --> 00:55:27,825
It's good luck. You always keep
the handbill of your first bounty.

645
00:56:15,371 --> 00:56:16,790
That's accurate.

646
00:57:25,192 --> 00:57:28,278
Doctor, Django, how the hell are you?

647
00:57:29,321 --> 00:57:31,448
Who the hell have you got there?

648
00:57:31,615 --> 00:57:33,700
The Wilson-Lowe Gang.

649
00:57:33,992 --> 00:57:36,745
Who the hell
is the Wilson-Lowe Gang?

650
00:57:37,621 --> 00:57:42,125
Bad Chuck Wilson and meaner
Bobby Lowe and three of their acolytes.

651
00:57:43,585 --> 00:57:45,963
Leave them out here,
they ain't going nowhere.

652
00:57:46,129 --> 00:57:50,342
Why don't you come in out of the snow
and get yourselves some coffee?

653
00:57:50,509 --> 00:57:53,178
We had a birthday yesterday.
Got some cake.

654
00:57:53,637 --> 00:57:55,138
Pretty good.

655
00:58:28,213 --> 00:58:31,633
Keep moving.
Get on up to that auction block.

656
00:58:32,968 --> 00:58:35,971
Don't let that mud slow you down.
Keep going.

657
00:58:38,765 --> 00:58:40,434
Come on.

658
00:58:51,903 --> 00:58:53,572
Keep going.

659
00:58:55,657 --> 00:58:57,367
"Broomhilda Von Shaft.

660
00:58:57,534 --> 00:58:59,453
Age 27.

661
00:58:59,619 --> 00:59:01,913
'R' on right cheek.

662
00:59:02,748 --> 00:59:05,125
Calvin Candie."

663
00:59:05,292 --> 00:59:09,713
He owns the fourth biggest cotton
plantation in Mississippi, Candyland.

664
00:59:09,880 --> 00:59:11,173
Candyland?

665
00:59:11,381 --> 00:59:14,843
-Oh, you've heard of it.
-Ain't no slave ain't heard of Candyland.

666
00:59:15,010 --> 00:59:17,387
Well, apparently,
that's where your wife is...

667
00:59:17,554 --> 00:59:20,390
...and that's the repellant gentleman
who owns her.

668
00:59:20,557 --> 00:59:23,101
Let's hope she works
in the house, not the field.

669
00:59:23,268 --> 00:59:25,312
Oh, no, she ain't no field nigger.

670
00:59:25,562 --> 00:59:27,856
She-- She pretty.

671
00:59:28,231 --> 00:59:30,400
And she talk good too.

672
00:59:31,485 --> 00:59:33,737
But when they tore her back up...

673
00:59:33,904 --> 00:59:37,365
...and then they burned
that runaway "R" on her cheek...

674
00:59:38,075 --> 00:59:39,409
...they goddamned her.

675
00:59:43,997 --> 00:59:47,667
She ain't no field nigger but ain't good
enough for the house no more.

676
00:59:47,834 --> 00:59:51,171
-They gonna try to make her a comfort girl.
-What's a comfort--?

677
00:59:51,922 --> 00:59:53,340
Not while I got freedom.

678
00:59:55,008 --> 00:59:57,094
Not while I got my gun.

679
01:00:00,263 --> 01:00:01,848
So do we offer to buy her?

680
01:00:04,309 --> 01:00:05,894
So...

681
01:00:07,270 --> 01:00:08,855
...say...

682
01:00:10,899 --> 01:00:14,069
...a man wants to buy a horse.

683
01:00:14,236 --> 01:00:16,530
Needs to buy a horse.

684
01:00:17,405 --> 01:00:20,242
He walks up to the farmer's farm,
knocks on the door...

685
01:00:20,408 --> 01:00:24,162
...and asks the farmer to buy his horse.
You know what the farmer says?

686
01:00:24,329 --> 01:00:26,873
The farmer says no.

687
01:00:27,999 --> 01:00:32,879
Well, I say fuck that farmer.
And I'm stealing that horse.

688
01:00:33,046 --> 01:00:35,340
Fair enough.
But now you're a horse thief...

689
01:00:35,507 --> 01:00:37,259
...and they hang horse thieves.

690
01:00:37,425 --> 01:00:41,429
The horse goes back to its original owner
because the horse is his property.

691
01:00:41,596 --> 01:00:45,100
We need her and we need
a bill of sale.

692
01:00:45,267 --> 01:00:47,811
If we ain't gonna buy her,
how we gonna get her?

693
01:00:49,062 --> 01:00:52,566
May I offer an alternative
plan of action?

694
01:00:52,899 --> 01:00:54,234
Go ahead.

695
01:00:54,568 --> 01:00:55,986
So...

696
01:00:56,278 --> 01:01:01,283
...the man walks up to the farmer's farm,
he knocks on the farmer's door...

697
01:01:01,449 --> 01:01:06,413
...and asks not to buy the horse,
but the farm.

698
01:01:06,955 --> 01:01:10,125
And makes an offer so ridiculous...

699
01:01:10,292 --> 01:01:12,794
...the farmer is forced to say yes.

700
01:01:13,753 --> 01:01:16,673
-We gonna offer to buy Candyland?
-No, it's far too big.

701
01:01:16,840 --> 01:01:20,177
But apparently this farmer
ain't all about the farm.

702
01:01:21,178 --> 01:01:23,513
How much do you know
about Mandingo fighting?

703
01:01:23,680 --> 01:01:24,723
What?

704
01:01:24,890 --> 01:01:27,225
Can you convincingly masquerade
as someone...

705
01:01:27,392 --> 01:01:29,519
...who is an expert
on Mandingo fighting?

706
01:01:29,686 --> 01:01:30,729
Why?

707
01:01:31,062 --> 01:01:34,608
<i>Because my character is that of</i>
<i>a big money buyer from Düsseldorf...</i>

708
01:01:34,774 --> 01:01:38,153
<i>...here in Greenville to buy my way</i>
<i>into the Mandingo fight game.</i>

709
01:01:38,320 --> 01:01:42,157
<i>And your character is a Mandingo expert</i>
<i>I hired to help me do it.</i>

710
01:01:42,324 --> 01:01:44,326
<i>They call that "One-Eyed Charly."</i>

711
01:01:52,042 --> 01:01:54,878
We're here to see Mr. Calvin Candie.

712
01:01:58,924 --> 01:02:00,842
Thank you.

713
01:02:01,593 --> 01:02:04,095
You want me to play a black slaver?

714
01:02:04,429 --> 01:02:07,057
Ain't nothing lower than a black slaver.

715
01:02:07,265 --> 01:02:10,977
A black slaver is lower than
the head house nigger...

716
01:02:11,269 --> 01:02:13,772
...and, buddy, that's pretty fucking low.

717
01:02:14,731 --> 01:02:16,483
Then play him that way.

718
01:02:16,650 --> 01:02:20,820
Give me your black slaver.

719
01:02:32,374 --> 01:02:34,084
Dr. Schultz.

720
01:02:34,251 --> 01:02:36,962
-Good to see you again.
-Mr. Moguy.

721
01:02:37,128 --> 01:02:41,299
Thank you for your assistance in creating
the opportunity for this appointment.

722
01:02:41,466 --> 01:02:43,260
Nonsense, it's my job.

723
01:02:43,426 --> 01:02:46,346
So this is the One-Eyed Charly
I've heard so much about.

724
01:02:46,513 --> 01:02:48,890
Yes, this is Django Freeman.

725
01:02:49,057 --> 01:02:51,851
Django, this is Mr. Candie's lawyer,
Leonide Moguy.

726
01:02:52,018 --> 01:02:53,770
Just call me Leo.

727
01:02:53,937 --> 01:02:57,274
Calvin's in the Julius Caesar room.
You all wanna follow me?

728
01:02:57,440 --> 01:03:00,026
How long have you been associated
with Mr. Candie?

729
01:03:00,193 --> 01:03:04,406
Calvin's father and I were about 11 when
we went to boarding school together.

730
01:03:04,572 --> 01:03:07,450
Calvin's father's father
put me through law school.

731
01:03:07,617 --> 01:03:10,745
One could almost say I was raised
to be Calvin's lawyer.

732
01:03:10,912 --> 01:03:13,164
One could almost say youse a nigger.

733
01:03:13,498 --> 01:03:15,000
What did you say?

734
01:03:15,166 --> 01:03:17,794
-I said--
-Nothing, he's just being cheeky.

735
01:03:18,336 --> 01:03:22,757
Now, anything else about Mr. Candie
that I should know before I meet him?

736
01:03:22,924 --> 01:03:25,135
Yes, he is a bit of a Francophile.

737
01:03:25,302 --> 01:03:26,845
What civilized people aren't?

738
01:03:27,012 --> 01:03:29,347
And he prefers Monsieur Candie
to Mr. Candie.

739
01:03:31,891 --> 01:03:36,396
{\an8}He doesn't speak French. Don't speak
French to him, it'll embarrass him.

740
01:03:38,940 --> 01:03:41,318
Get back on top, now. Turn around.

741
01:03:41,484 --> 01:03:42,986
There you go.

742
01:03:43,153 --> 01:03:44,738
There you go.

743
01:03:46,406 --> 01:03:48,908
Why do you want to get
in the Mandingo business?

744
01:03:51,494 --> 01:03:55,415
You don't intend to allow your second
to make the proper introductions?

745
01:03:56,374 --> 01:03:59,544
Quit stalling, now.
Answer the question.

746
01:04:02,130 --> 01:04:04,132
The awful truth?

747
01:04:04,341 --> 01:04:08,261
I'm bored.
This seems like a good bit of fun.

748
01:04:13,224 --> 01:04:15,226
Well, come on over.

749
01:04:15,393 --> 01:04:18,146
We got us a fight going on
that's a good bit of fun.

750
01:04:21,858 --> 01:04:23,651
Won't you accompany me to the bar?

751
01:04:32,869 --> 01:04:36,164
You don't wear a hat in the house,
white man. Even I know that.

752
01:04:44,047 --> 01:04:45,882
-Dr. Schultz.
-What a rare pleasure.

753
01:04:46,049 --> 01:04:47,467
Keep fighting, niggers.

754
01:04:47,634 --> 01:04:49,427
And I might add, an honor.

755
01:04:49,594 --> 01:04:52,389
Honor to meet you.
Have a seat, the pleasure's mine.

756
01:04:52,555 --> 01:04:56,017
Get free man Django here
whatever he wants.

757
01:04:56,184 --> 01:04:58,520
And I'll have sweet tea and bourbon.

758
01:05:18,123 --> 01:05:21,292
Use your weight, boy, use your weight!
There you go.

759
01:05:21,543 --> 01:05:23,753
He's much bigger and stronger!

760
01:05:23,920 --> 01:05:25,463
Come on, now!

761
01:05:25,630 --> 01:05:28,174
He's not doing what I told him,
for God's sakes.

762
01:05:28,508 --> 01:05:30,552
Bravo, bravo, Luigi.

763
01:05:32,220 --> 01:05:35,515
Come on, now, boy!
It's a fight to the death!

764
01:05:36,349 --> 01:05:38,268
You either hit him or are you ain't?

765
01:05:46,317 --> 01:05:48,820
Big Fred, come on!

766
01:05:49,320 --> 01:05:51,739
Turn him around! Now, come--!

767
01:05:54,617 --> 01:05:56,369
Use your strength, boy!

768
01:05:56,953 --> 01:05:59,497
Come on, now! Use your strength!

769
01:06:01,082 --> 01:06:02,792
There you go.

770
01:06:04,419 --> 01:06:05,670
There you go!

771
01:06:05,837 --> 01:06:06,880
Look at that.

772
01:06:07,714 --> 01:06:10,800
See, I told you to put some more power
in there.

773
01:06:10,967 --> 01:06:12,969
Do what I told you, boy.

774
01:06:13,136 --> 01:06:14,804
There you go.

775
01:06:14,971 --> 01:06:16,139
No.

776
01:06:16,306 --> 01:06:17,348
Do what I told you!

777
01:06:17,515 --> 01:06:21,019
Blind him black, boy! Blind him black!

778
01:06:22,645 --> 01:06:24,230
Oh, no, Luigi.

779
01:06:26,483 --> 01:06:27,525
Yeah!

780
01:06:45,043 --> 01:06:46,085
Finish him.

781
01:06:50,507 --> 01:06:52,091
Go on, boy, finish him.

782
01:06:56,721 --> 01:06:59,807
That's why they call him Big Fred.
Worth every penny.

783
01:07:00,225 --> 01:07:02,060
Well, arrivederci, Luigi.

784
01:07:02,227 --> 01:07:04,479
Come on up, now, boy.
Get yourself a rest.

785
01:07:04,646 --> 01:07:07,440
You did a fine job. A real fine job.

786
01:07:08,024 --> 01:07:09,609
Mercedes.

787
01:07:30,880 --> 01:07:32,340
Tequila.

788
01:07:42,100 --> 01:07:43,810
What's your name?

789
01:07:45,853 --> 01:07:47,438
Django.

790
01:07:49,732 --> 01:07:51,526
Can you spell it?

791
01:07:53,528 --> 01:07:57,532
D-J-A-N-G-O.

792
01:07:59,075 --> 01:08:00,618
The D is silent.

793
01:08:01,160 --> 01:08:02,745
I know.

794
01:08:10,378 --> 01:08:13,840
Mr. Moguy, I want you to take care
of my new boy here.

795
01:08:14,007 --> 01:08:18,303
You find him a room with a soft bed,
then bring him up a pony to lick his pole.

796
01:08:18,469 --> 01:08:21,556
Be ready to travel to Candyland
tomorrow morning, you hear?

797
01:08:21,723 --> 01:08:23,099
-Yes, sir.
-Before you go--

798
01:08:23,266 --> 01:08:27,020
Roscoe, get Fred here a tall beer.

799
01:08:30,481 --> 01:08:33,568
You enjoy that, boy. You've earned it.

800
01:08:33,735 --> 01:08:35,111
Yes, sir.

801
01:08:44,120 --> 01:08:45,288
What's your name, boy?

802
01:08:45,872 --> 01:08:48,708
His name is Django Freeman.

803
01:08:51,711 --> 01:08:53,379
Where'd you dig him up?

804
01:08:53,546 --> 01:08:57,467
A fortuitous turn of events brought
Django and myself together.

805
01:08:58,426 --> 01:09:00,720
I've heard tell about you.

806
01:09:01,179 --> 01:09:04,098
You been telling everybody
them Mandingos ain't no good.

807
01:09:04,265 --> 01:09:08,019
Nothing nobody is selling
is worth buying. I'm curious.

808
01:09:08,186 --> 01:09:10,688
What makes you
such a Mandingo expert?

809
01:09:12,690 --> 01:09:15,109
I'm curious what makes you so curious.

810
01:09:18,446 --> 01:09:21,240
-What did you say, boy?
-Calm down, Butch.

811
01:09:21,532 --> 01:09:22,825
No offense given...

812
01:09:23,534 --> 01:09:24,786
...none taken.

813
01:09:24,952 --> 01:09:26,537
Monsieur Candie...

814
01:09:26,704 --> 01:09:30,500
...I'd appreciate if you could direct
your line of inquiry toward me.

815
01:09:30,667 --> 01:09:32,001
One...

816
01:09:32,627 --> 01:09:35,922
...you do not have a drink.
Can I get you a refreshment?

817
01:09:36,089 --> 01:09:38,591
Yes. I'll have a beer.

818
01:09:38,758 --> 01:09:41,052
Roscoe, a beer for the man
with the beard...

819
01:09:41,219 --> 01:09:45,056
...and I will have a Polynesian
Pearl Diver. Do not spare the rum.

820
01:09:45,223 --> 01:09:46,683
Doc...

821
01:09:47,392 --> 01:09:50,728
...I am a seasoned slaver. You are--
Well, you are a neophyte.

822
01:09:50,895 --> 01:09:53,981
I'm simply trying to ascertain
if this cowboy here...

823
01:09:54,148 --> 01:09:56,109
...is taking advantage of you.

824
01:09:57,402 --> 01:10:00,988
With all due respect,
Monsieur Candie...

825
01:10:01,155 --> 01:10:03,324
...I didn't seek you out for your advice.

826
01:10:03,491 --> 01:10:07,870
I sought you out to purchase a fighting
nigger at above top-dollar market price.

827
01:10:08,037 --> 01:10:11,290
I was under the impression,
when you granted me an audience...

828
01:10:11,457 --> 01:10:13,710
...it would be to discuss business.

829
01:10:16,337 --> 01:10:18,673
Well, we weren't talking business yet.

830
01:10:18,840 --> 01:10:21,509
We were discussing my curiosity.

831
01:10:23,428 --> 01:10:24,470
Thank you.

832
01:10:24,637 --> 01:10:27,515
Roscoe, Coco, go outside and play.

833
01:10:29,350 --> 01:10:32,603
Sheba, you stay right there.

834
01:10:32,854 --> 01:10:34,439
I know you didn't mean me.

835
01:10:37,775 --> 01:10:39,235
German.

836
01:10:39,694 --> 01:10:41,320
Now, according to Moguy...

837
01:10:41,571 --> 01:10:43,531
...if I do business with you...

838
01:10:43,698 --> 01:10:45,700
...I'm doing business with both y'all.

839
01:10:45,867 --> 01:10:48,327
He does the eyeballing,
you the billfold?

840
01:10:48,494 --> 01:10:52,248
Well, you don't make it sound
too flattering, but more or less, yeah.

841
01:10:54,751 --> 01:10:55,877
So...

842
01:10:56,377 --> 01:10:59,964
...Bright Boy, Moguy tells me
you looked over my African flesh...

843
01:11:00,131 --> 01:11:02,383
...and you was none too impressed,
huh?

844
01:11:02,550 --> 01:11:04,051
Not for top dollar.

845
01:11:06,053 --> 01:11:08,055
Then we got nothing more
to talk about.

846
01:11:08,222 --> 01:11:10,391
You wanna buy a beat-ass
nigger from me...

847
01:11:10,558 --> 01:11:13,019
...those are the beat-ass niggers
I wanna sell.

848
01:11:13,186 --> 01:11:15,813
He don't wanna buy the niggers
you wanna sell.

849
01:11:15,980 --> 01:11:19,192
He wants the nigger
you don't wanna sell.

850
01:11:19,400 --> 01:11:23,988
Well, I don't sell the niggers
I don't wanna sell.

851
01:11:25,948 --> 01:11:29,619
Well, you won't sell your best.

852
01:11:29,786 --> 01:11:32,163
You won't even sell your second best.

853
01:11:32,330 --> 01:11:35,833
But your third best?
You don't want to sell him either.

854
01:11:36,000 --> 01:11:40,379
But if I made you an offer so ridiculous
you'd be forced to consider it...

855
01:11:41,214 --> 01:11:42,882
...who knows what could happen?

856
01:11:45,343 --> 01:11:47,553
And what do you consider ridiculous?

857
01:11:48,429 --> 01:11:53,017
For a truly talented specimen,
the right nigger?

858
01:11:54,477 --> 01:11:56,354
How much would you say, Django?

859
01:11:59,732 --> 01:12:01,943
Twelve thousand dollars.

860
01:12:06,239 --> 01:12:10,034
Well, gentlemen,
you had my curiosity...

861
01:12:10,201 --> 01:12:12,495
...but now you have my attention.

862
01:12:25,925 --> 01:12:28,135
Willie. Willie.

863
01:12:28,302 --> 01:12:30,596
Hold up. Hold up.

864
01:12:31,597 --> 01:12:34,183
-Good morning, gentlemen.
-Good Dr. Schultz.

865
01:12:34,559 --> 01:12:38,187
-Beautiful morning, isn't it?
-You couldn't have picked a better one.

866
01:12:38,354 --> 01:12:41,315
Won't you take a ride with us
here in the victoria?

867
01:12:41,482 --> 01:12:42,775
Oh, thank you very much.

868
01:12:42,942 --> 01:12:45,403
You can tie your horse up back there.

869
01:12:53,369 --> 01:12:54,996
Django.

870
01:12:59,458 --> 01:13:03,212
Where I part company from many
of my phrenologist colleagues...

871
01:13:03,379 --> 01:13:06,465
...is I believe there is a level
above bright...

872
01:13:06,632 --> 01:13:09,427
...above talented, above loyal...

873
01:13:09,594 --> 01:13:12,805
...that a nigger can aspire to.

874
01:13:12,972 --> 01:13:17,476
Say, one nigger that just pops up
in 10,000.

875
01:13:17,727 --> 01:13:19,270
The exceptional nigger.

876
01:13:20,271 --> 01:13:22,815
Bright day, huh, Bright Boy?

877
01:13:23,441 --> 01:13:24,650
The sun is up.

878
01:13:25,776 --> 01:13:27,695
It's shining on all of us.

879
01:13:32,408 --> 01:13:34,201
Have a seat, doc.

880
01:13:34,577 --> 01:13:36,829
Thank you. Quite an honor.

881
01:13:36,996 --> 01:13:38,789
-The honor is all ours.
-Thank you.

882
01:13:39,206 --> 01:13:42,335
<i>But I do believe that given time...</i>

883
01:13:42,501 --> 01:13:45,713
...exceptional niggers
like Bright Boy here...

884
01:13:46,130 --> 01:13:48,674
...become if not frequent...

885
01:13:49,300 --> 01:13:51,218
...more frequent.

886
01:13:52,720 --> 01:13:54,096
Right, boy?

887
01:13:54,972 --> 01:13:57,475
You are that 1 in 10,000.

888
01:13:57,642 --> 01:14:00,770
The name of the game is keep up,
not catch up, nigger.

889
01:14:16,619 --> 01:14:19,413
-Touch your guns, you die.
-Everybody calm down.

890
01:14:19,705 --> 01:14:21,832
Now, I saw the whole thing.
No harm done.

891
01:14:21,999 --> 01:14:25,169
-Are you kidding me? This nigger just--
-I said no harm done!

892
01:14:25,336 --> 01:14:27,338
Now take your hand off your pistol!

893
01:14:28,965 --> 01:14:32,176
Butch, that means you too.

894
01:14:32,969 --> 01:14:35,137
Everybody stop antagonizing
my guest.

895
01:14:37,264 --> 01:14:39,642
Hoot, get back up on your horse.

896
01:14:40,309 --> 01:14:41,852
He broke my collarbone.

897
01:14:42,019 --> 01:14:44,563
For God's sake,
somebody please help Hoot here...

898
01:14:44,730 --> 01:14:46,440
...back up on his goddamn horse.

899
01:14:46,607 --> 01:14:49,568
-Yes, sir, boss.
-Oh, now, you are one lucky nigger.

900
01:14:50,403 --> 01:14:52,405
Better listen to your boss, white boy.

901
01:14:52,571 --> 01:14:55,032
I'm gonna go walking
in the moonlight with you.

902
01:14:55,199 --> 01:14:56,993
You wanna hold my hand?

903
01:15:03,582 --> 01:15:06,377
Willie, take us home.

904
01:15:08,379 --> 01:15:10,381
Here we go. Start moving.

905
01:15:16,971 --> 01:15:18,431
Head them out.

906
01:16:03,642 --> 01:16:05,811
You got a problem
with your eyeball, boy?

907
01:16:05,978 --> 01:16:08,230
-No, sir.
-You want a boot heel in it?

908
01:16:09,523 --> 01:16:10,566
No, sir.

909
01:16:10,733 --> 01:16:13,486
Then you keep your goddamn eyeballs
off me.

910
01:16:13,736 --> 01:16:17,239
Flash that look at me again,
I'll give you a reason not to like me.

911
01:16:17,406 --> 01:16:18,949
Now move, nigger.

912
01:16:20,785 --> 01:16:22,995
You niggers are gonna
understand something.

913
01:16:23,162 --> 01:16:25,372
I'm worse than any
of these white men here.

914
01:16:25,539 --> 01:16:29,168
You get the molasses out your ass,
keep your goddamn eyeballs off me.

915
01:16:29,335 --> 01:16:32,046
He is a rambunctious sort, ain't he?

916
01:16:32,213 --> 01:16:33,422
Indeed.

917
01:16:35,966 --> 01:16:39,428
May we stop for a moment
so I may put a word in my man's ear?

918
01:16:39,595 --> 01:16:43,307
I'm expecting to fall in love once I see
the specimens at Candyland...

919
01:16:43,474 --> 01:16:44,934
...so before that moment...

920
01:16:45,101 --> 01:16:48,813
...it would be good if I could have
a confidential strategy meeting...

921
01:16:48,979 --> 01:16:51,107
...with my confidant.

922
01:16:54,110 --> 01:16:55,903
What the hell you doing?

923
01:16:56,070 --> 01:16:58,656
I confirmed that Broomhilda's
at Candyland.

924
01:17:01,992 --> 01:17:04,745
-You're sure it's her?
-He didn't call her by name...

925
01:17:04,912 --> 01:17:08,457
...but she's a young lady, whip marks
on her back and speaks German.

926
01:17:08,624 --> 01:17:10,334
While it's not wise to assume...

927
01:17:10,501 --> 01:17:12,962
...in this instance, I think it's pretty safe.

928
01:17:13,129 --> 01:17:14,588
Point being...

929
01:17:14,755 --> 01:17:17,758
...don't get so carried away
with your retribution.

930
01:17:17,925 --> 01:17:19,677
You lose sight of why we're here.

931
01:17:19,844 --> 01:17:24,306
-You think I lost sight of that?
-Yes, I do. Stop antagonizing Candie.

932
01:17:24,473 --> 01:17:29,603
You're going to blow this whole charade,
or more than likely get us both killed.

933
01:17:29,770 --> 01:17:34,483
And I, for one, don't intend to die
in Chickasaw County, Mississippi, U.S.A.

934
01:17:34,650 --> 01:17:38,028
I'm not antagonizing him.
I'm intriguing him.

935
01:17:38,195 --> 01:17:40,990
You're yelling abuse
at these poor slaves.

936
01:17:41,157 --> 01:17:43,409
I recall the man...

937
01:17:43,617 --> 01:17:46,704
...who had me kill another man
in front of his son...

938
01:17:46,871 --> 01:17:48,956
...and he didn't bat a eye.

939
01:17:50,166 --> 01:17:51,208
You remember that?

940
01:17:53,335 --> 01:17:54,795
Yeah, of course I remember.

941
01:17:54,962 --> 01:17:58,507
What you said was that
this is my world...

942
01:17:59,258 --> 01:18:01,677
...and in my world you gotta get dirty.

943
01:18:02,428 --> 01:18:05,639
So that's what I'm doing,
I'm getting dirty.

944
01:18:09,059 --> 01:18:12,563
Well, you're paraphrasing a tad...

945
01:18:13,689 --> 01:18:15,774
...but that was the general gist.

946
01:18:19,570 --> 01:18:21,488
See you at Candyland.

947
01:18:28,704 --> 01:18:31,665
All right, niggers, back at it.

948
01:18:32,541 --> 01:18:34,793
That means you too, Moonlight.

949
01:19:21,757 --> 01:19:22,800
I'll be.

950
01:19:23,175 --> 01:19:24,802
D'Artagnan!

951
01:19:25,052 --> 01:19:28,180
Now, boy, why do a fool thing
like run off?

952
01:19:28,347 --> 01:19:30,724
I can't fight no more, Monsieur Candie.

953
01:19:30,891 --> 01:19:32,017
Yes, you can.

954
01:19:32,184 --> 01:19:35,437
You might not be able to win,
but your ass can fight.

955
01:19:35,896 --> 01:19:39,775
Mr. Stonesipher, would you shut these
dogs up? I cannot hear myself think.

956
01:19:39,942 --> 01:19:42,528
Quieten down, Marsha!
Marsha, hush up!

957
01:19:42,695 --> 01:19:44,154
Marsha! Hush up!

958
01:19:44,697 --> 01:19:48,242
Hey! Get these goddamn dogs
away from this nigger!

959
01:19:57,293 --> 01:20:01,714
-Well, now, boy, get on out that tree.
-Yes, sir.

960
01:20:25,112 --> 01:20:27,072
How long was he loose?

961
01:20:27,364 --> 01:20:30,534
A night. Day.

962
01:20:30,784 --> 01:20:32,703
Half the other night.

963
01:20:33,412 --> 01:20:35,247
How far he get off the property?

964
01:20:35,414 --> 01:20:40,294
About 20 miles off prop.
Pretty far considering that limp he got.

965
01:20:42,046 --> 01:20:45,382
Mr. Moguy, who was D'Artagnan
supposed to fight on Friday?

966
01:20:45,549 --> 01:20:47,509
One of this new lot.

967
01:20:48,260 --> 01:20:51,388
Way he looks now, a blind Indian
wouldn't bet a bead on him.

968
01:20:51,555 --> 01:20:54,391
Please, Monsieur Candie,
I ain't got it in me no more.

969
01:20:54,558 --> 01:20:57,936
Now, now, now. Now, no begging.

970
01:20:58,145 --> 01:21:00,939
No playing on my soft heart.

971
01:21:04,151 --> 01:21:07,237
-You in trouble now, son.
-Yes, sir.

972
01:21:09,490 --> 01:21:13,285
You know, I done paid $500 for you.

973
01:21:13,452 --> 01:21:15,662
When I pay $500...

974
01:21:15,829 --> 01:21:20,084
...I expect to get five fights out of a nigger
before he roll over and play dead.

975
01:21:20,250 --> 01:21:21,293
Sir.

976
01:21:21,460 --> 01:21:24,505
Gotta understand
I'm running a business here.

977
01:21:24,880 --> 01:21:27,674
-You fought three fights.
-But I won every one.

978
01:21:27,841 --> 01:21:29,301
Yes, you did. Yes, you did.

979
01:21:29,468 --> 01:21:33,180
But that last one, you muddled the line
between winning and losing.

980
01:21:36,266 --> 01:21:38,394
Still, the fact remains:

981
01:21:38,602 --> 01:21:42,272
I pay $500, I want five goddamn fights.

982
01:21:42,606 --> 01:21:44,858
So, what about my $500, huh?

983
01:21:46,819 --> 01:21:49,154
What about my $500?

984
01:21:50,155 --> 01:21:51,740
You gonna reimburse me?

985
01:21:57,913 --> 01:22:00,249
You even know
what "reimburse" means?

986
01:22:08,632 --> 01:22:10,384
I'll reimburse you.

987
01:22:14,179 --> 01:22:15,305
You will?

988
01:22:16,598 --> 01:22:18,058
Yep.

989
01:22:20,811 --> 01:22:23,105
You'll pay $500...

990
01:22:23,730 --> 01:22:27,276
...for practically a one-eyed old Joe
ain't fit to push a broom?

991
01:22:27,443 --> 01:22:28,485
No, he won't.

992
01:22:30,612 --> 01:22:33,031
He just tired of you
toying with him is all.

993
01:22:33,782 --> 01:22:35,742
